<dl id="n53079b"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n53" href="#n53079b">N53 (VI.B.46)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n53all.htm#n53079b"> 79(b)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> bearlagair na / saer / (vernac of masons) <small>Green</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n53079b"><li>FW 223.05 </li><li><a href="../../flex/kb/lexkb.htm#n53079b">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/kb/l39kb.htm#n53079b">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n53079b">MS BL 47477-274</ms> </li><li>JJA 51:399 <a name="kad9" href="../../FF/fdra/kda.htm#kbd7">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/kb/kbd7.htm#n53079b">Draft: II.1&sect;2.7</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources"><mark>B&eacute;rlagair na S&aacute;er</mark> <p>Prof. Kuno Meyer shewed (<cite>Revue Celtique</cite>, vol. xiii, p. 505) that the word <i>b&eacute;rlaga</i> does not mean, as had been supposed, &lsquo;language of craft&rsquo;; nor should it be translated &lsquo;jargon&rsquo;: it is merely an adaptation of the English word &lsquo;vernacular&rsquo;. The &lsquo;<mark>Vernacular of the Masons</mark>&rsquo; is therefore the proper translation for the name of the language now to be studied.</p> <small> R.A. Stewart MacAlister, <a name="MSLI" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#MSLI"><cite title="source">The Secret Languages of Ireland</cite></a> (Jan 1937) B&eacute;rlagair na S&aacute;er, 225</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
